jgH1CWmSYX4.title: Western Towboat PACIFIC TITAN, Fremont to Harbor Island (Seattle)
jgH1CWmSYX4.description: Ever wonder what a tugboat looks like on the inside? Or what the view from a tugboat looks like? I joined the crew of PACIFIC TITAN for a ride down to Harbor Island on 10/2/13. I'm always surprised at how many landlubbers don't realize that so much of a tugboat lives BELOW the waterline. If you pause the video around the 18 second mark, you'll see that the engine room is very big- this whole space is below the waterline. The galley and some cabins are just above the waterline, then there's another deck with cabins above that before you get to the wheelhouse. Tugs come in varying shapes and sizes. This one is about 12 years old but looks brand new.

kaibn46f5FM.title: How To: Tie a Figure 8 Knot
kaibn46f5FM.description:
The Figure 8 is one of the most versatile knots for kayakers, rafters, canoeists, swiftwater rescue professionals, climbers and other outdoor folks to learn and use. It works for making a tiedown point along a length of rope and as a stopper knot at the end of one. It's frequently tied at the end of a rescue line to secure it to an anchor point or a rescue belt, often with a carabiner. Climbers use it to securely tie into a climbing harness. You can also tie two different lengths of rope together with it. And a great thing about this knot is that it's easy to untie, even after it's been under load.

Spend some time practicing your knot tying; you can't be on the water all the time! Ropes are an essential part of a boater's gear inventory. They're used for lashing gear into or onto the boat. They tie you up to shore. They're essential for setting up a z-drag and other rescue and safety systems. To do just about anything with a rope requires putting knots in it.   

In this video, NRS Repairs Guru Josh Gile demonstrates different ways of tying the great Figure 8 Knot.

hlB8pcXgzyc.description:
If you looking for the ideal Caribbean cookie, you'll love this coconut mango cookie. In the recipe I'll show you how to make delicious coconut mango cookies, which are somewhat crumbly in texture with a taste similar to shortbread. The shredded coconut along with the dried mango pieces will enhance the overall flavor.

You'll Need...

2 sticks of butter (soft)
2/3 cup superfine sugar
1 egg yolk
2 teaspoon vanilla extract
2 1/4 cups flour (all purpose)
pinch salt
1/2 cup shredded coconut (unsweetened)
1/4 cup dried sweetened mango (chopped)
